DocuSign Envelope ID: 172D4642-AEE0-41D6-99D6-E547425FF009 ITC A FORTIS COMPANY CONTRIBUTION IN AID OF CONSTRUCTION AGREEMENT NON-TAXABLE PROJECT THIS CONTRIBUTION IN AID OF CONSTRUCTION AGREEMENT (the "Agreement") is made between Cerro Gordo Wind, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Requestor") with an address of 700 Universe Blvd., Juno Beach, FL 33408 and ITC Midwest LLC, a Michigan limited liability company ("ITCMW") whose address is 123 5th Street SE, Cedar Rapids, Iowa 52401, and is effective on the last date of execution indicated on the signature page(s), subject to the terms hereof. Requestor and ITCMW may be referred to individually herein as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties." Recitals A. Requestor has asked ITCMW to reduce the duration of the outage on Requestor's Cerro Gordo Wind Substation so ITCMW can perform work on its' Hancock to Emery 161 kV transmission line. B. ITCMW will split the Hancock to Emery 161 kV transmission line outage into two separate projects by installing temporary equipment along the transmission line near the Cerro Gordo Wind Substation, in an effort to reduce the duration of the outage from an estimate of 5.5 weeks to an estimate of 5 days targeted to start in or around March 2024, which estimate is not a guarantee (the "Work"). C. ITCMW is willing to perform the Work, provided it is paid for the cost of doing so. Agreement In consideration of the grants, covenants and agreements herein, the Parties agree as follows: 1. Work under this Agreement cannot commence until the filing with and acceptance of this Agreement by, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC"). 2. Upon receipt of payment of the Projected Cost (as defined below), Requestor authorizes ITCMW to proceed with the Work. 3. Requestor shall pay ITCMW for the Projected Cost of the Work, which shall include the cost of all labor and overhead to complete the Work. ITCMW estimates the cost of the Work to be Forty-Seven Thousand Four Hundred Eighty-Two and 51/100 dollars ($47,482.51) (the "Projected Cost"). Requestor's payment of the Projected Cost is due to ITCMW upon acceptance of this Agreement by FERC. ITCMW shall invoice Requestor upon FERC acceptance of this Agreement and Requestor shall pay the invoice within thirty (30) days indicating that the payment is for ITCMW Project Name: NextEra Cerro Gordo Temporary Construction. 4. If the actual cost of the Work is less than the Projected Cost paid by Requestor, ITCMW will, within one hundred and eighty (180) days after completion of the Work, refund the excess to Requestor. If the actual cost of the Work exceeds the Projected Cost paid by Requestor, Requestor shall pay ITCMW the balance of the actual cost of the Work within thirty (30) days of receipt of an invoice from ITCMW. 1 DocuSign Envelope ID: 172D4642-AEE0-41D6-99D6-E547425FF009 5. Requestor's payment for the Work will be classified as a Contribution In Aid of Construction ("CIAC") payment, which is intended to cover the full cost of the Work. The estimate does not include a tax gross-up because the Work does not appear to be taxable. Notwithstanding and in the event the project is deemed taxable, Requestor agrees to reimburse ITCMW for taxes, including penalty and interest payments, if any, imposed by the Internal Revenue Service or other taxing authority with jurisdiction over the Work within thirty (30) days of notice provided by ITCMW of such tax obligation. 6. ITCMW shall plan, schedule, and perform the Work and ITCMW shall solely determine the manner and method of the Work. ITCMW shall use commercially reasonable efforts to promptly commence and diligently pursue completion of the Work. 7. ITCMW shall not be responsible for delays caused by strikes, work stoppage, lockouts, acts of God (including inclement weather), delays attributable to Requestor or Requestor's employees, agents, contractors or affiliates, other public or private utilities, the permitting or escorting authorities, or by any other cause beyond the control of ITCMW; nor will ITCMW be responsible for delays that ITCMW, in its sole discretion, determines to be necessary for reasons of safety and/or system requirements. 8. This Agreement is contingent upon ITCMW obtaining all necessary permits and authority to perform the Work. In the event ITCMW fails to satisfy this condition precedent, no Work shall begin and ITCMW shall refund the initial payment of the Projected Cost to Requestor without further obligation or recourse by either Party. 9. ITCMW DISCLAIMS ANY AND ALL WARRANTIES OR REPRESENTATIONS PERTAINING TO THE WORK THAT ARE NOT EXPRESSLY SET FORTH IN THIS AGREEMENT, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO EXPRESS OR IMPLIED WARRANTIES AS TO FITNESS OR DESIGN AND ALL EQUIPMENT PROVIDED HEREUNDER WILL BE PROVIDED AS-IS. 10. Requestor (for purposes of this section, "Indemnitor") shall to the maximum extent allowed by law fully indemnify, defend and hold harmless ITCMW and its respective corporate parents and affiliates, employees, agents, contractors, officers, directors, and/or members and managers, as the case may be, (for purposes of this section, "Indemnitee(s)") from and against all claims, losses, demands, causes of action, enforcement proceedings, suits, and other liabilities of any nature, including but not limited to personal property damages, personal injuries or deaths, and including related expenses, costs and reasonable attorneys' fees to the extent arising out of, resulting from, or caused by: (a) negligent acts, errors or omissions, or willful misconduct of the Indemnitor, its employees, agents, contractors or affiliates; or (b) a breach by Indemnitor or any of its employees, agents, contractors or affiliates of any obligations in this Agreement. Indemnitor shall have the right to control the defense and settlement of all such actions or claims; as long as any settlement includes a full and final release of all claims against the Indemnitee(s). The Indemnitee(s) shall promptly notify the Indemnitor in writing of the claim and provide such information and take all such actions at the expense of the Indemnitor as may be reasonably requested by it in connection with such settlement or defense. The indemnity set forth in this section shall survive a termination or expiration of this Agreement. 11. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, under no circumstances shall either Party be liable to the other for the payment of any indirect, incidental, consequential, punitive or exemplary damages even if that Party has been made aware of the possibility of such damages; the Parties waive any and all such damages. 2

DISTRIBUTION-TRANSMISSION INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT BETWEEN ITC MIDWEST, LLC AND MAQUOKETA MUNICIPAL ELECTRIC UTILITY This DISTRIBUTION-TRANSMISSION INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT, herein termed “Agreement” between ITC Midwest, LLC, a Michigan limited liability company, 27175 Energy Way, Novi, Michigan, herein termed “Transmission Owner”, and Maquoketa Municipal Electric Utility, an Iowa municipal electric utility, herein termed “Interconnection Customer”. Transmission Owner and Interconnection Customer are sometimes referred to individually as “Party” and collectively as “Parties” where appropriate. WHEREAS, Transmission Owner and Interconnection Customer desire to enter into this Distribution-Transmission Interconnection Agreement for the purposes of replacing any prior agreements between predecessor parties, if any exist, and documenting existing interconnection practices which may include, among others: (a) describing the general facilities, and the ownership thereof, that shall be used at the interconnection site in establishing the Connection Facilities, respective ownership of facilities, obligations and rights of each of the Parties with respect to procurement, installation, operation and maintenance of such facilities; and (b) describing other procedures that are necessary to maintain safety, reliability and integrity on the Parties’ systems as a result of establishing the Connection Facilities at the interconnection site; and WHEREAS, Transmission Owner is an Appendix I member of the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and transmission service and functional control over facilities developed and owned by the Transmission Owner are provided pursuant to Midcontinent Independent System Operator’s (“MISO”) Open Access Transmission, Energy and Operating Reserve Markets Tariff (“Tariff” or “MISO Tariff”). NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and agreements below, the Parties agree as follows: SECTION 1. CONNECTION FACILITIES 1.1 General The Parties will provide, as specified in this Section 1, (and as shown in Exhibit A) certain electric facilities and associated appurtenances which will be used in the connection of the Interconnection Customer’s distribution substations or facilities, to the Transmission Owner’s electric transmission system.
1.1.1 Appendix B1 describes Interconnection Customer’s Connection Facilities and Appendix B2 describes Transmission Owner’s Connection Facilities, and sometimes individually or collectively referred to as the “Connection Facilities”. 1.1.2 Each Party shall bear the cost of maintaining, operating, repairing or replacing its Connection Facilities unless otherwise specified in this Agreement. 1.1.3 In the event future changes in either: (i) design or operation of Interconnection Customer’s system; (ii) Federal, state or local laws, regulations or codes; or (iii) design or operation of Transmission Owner’s system, later necessitate additional facilities or modifications to the then existing Connection Facilities herein, the Parties shall undertake such additions or modifications as may be necessary. 1.1.3.1 Before undertaking such future additions or modifications, the Parties shall consult, develop plans and coordinate schedules of activities. 1.1.3.2 The cost of such future additions or modifications to the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities shall be borne by the Interconnection Customer. 1.1.3.3 The cost of such future additions or modifications to the Transmission Owner Connection Facilities shall be recovered through the Transmission Owner’s Open Access Transmission Tariff on file with Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (‘FERC”), and shall not be directly assigned or charged to the Interconnection Customer, unless such cost is approved or required by the appropriate regulatory agency to be assigned to Interconnection Customer as agreed to by both Parties; or such future additions or modifications are requested by the Interconnection Customer and such request exceeds Transmission Owner’s guidelines for facilities provided to a similarly situated customer. 1.1.3.4 The ownership, operation, maintenance, and replacement responsibilities for any such future additions or modifications shall be made consistent with the responsibilities allocated in this Agreement. 1.2 Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities Interconnection Customer shall own, pay for and maintain Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities as described in Appendix B1. In addition to the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities described in Appendix B1, the Interconnection Customer is required to own, pay for and maintain the following Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities: 1.2.1 Interconnection billing and load control metering equipment which is compliant with MISO and Local Balancing Authority meter specifications. Note that the interconnection billing and load control metering equipment is currently metered
at the 69 kV level on the transmission system owned by the Transmission Owner. The metering is owned by WPPI Energy and the instrument transformers are owned by Interconnection Customer. Interconnection billing and load control metering will continue to be performed at the 69 kV level until modifications to the metering are mutually agreed to by both Parties. 1.2.2 Communication interface equipment and an Interconnection Customer’s Remote Terminal Unit which shall provide, via industry acceptable means, data to the Transmission Owner’s designated power control center. The Interconnection Customer shall provide to the applicable Meter Data Management Agent (the “MDMA”), Transmission Owner and, if necessary, to those third parties that require such data to calculate network load access via industry acceptable means to the billing metering data on terms acceptable to the Parties. The MDMA shall be responsible for reporting such data to MISO. 1.3 Transmission Owner Connection Facilities Transmission Owner shall own, pay for, operate and maintain Transmission Owner Interconnection Connection Facilities described in Appendix B2. 1.4 Connection Point and the Point of Change in Facility Ownership The Connection Point(s) and the Point(s) of Change in facility ownership between the Parties shall generally be the point(s) at which the Transmission Owner’s conductor meets the insulators on the Interconnection Customer’s dead-end structure in the Interconnection Customer’s substation(s) as further described in Appendix B2. 1.4.1 The Transmission Owner shall own the dead-end insulators mounted on the Interconnection Customer’s dead-end structure and any required attachment hardware (dead end shoes, compression dead end fittings, etc.). 1.4.2 The Transmission Owner shall own any required jumpers from the attachment hardware to the Point of Change of Ownership within the Interconnection Customer’s substation. 1.4.3 The Point of Delivery shall be at the Connection Point. 1.5 Transmission Owner Equipment Relocation Requested by Interconnection Customer If at any time Interconnection Customer requires those facilities located on its premises but provided and owned by Transmission Owner to be relocated on such premises and the requested relocation is not related to a modification of the Point of Connection, Transmission Owner shall at Interconnection Customer’s expense and upon Interconnection Customer’s request relocate the same or give permission for Interconnection Customer to relocate the same.
1.6 Facilities Added of Modified in the Future If and when additional facilities that are Connection Facilities are added or modified by Interconnection Customer or by Transmission Owner, it is agreed that each Party shall, at no cost to the other Party, install (or cause to be installed) facilities and/or protective systems that shall provide for the isolation of any electrical faults that occur on the interconnected systems of either the Interconnection Customer or Transmission Owner from having an effect on the other Party’s interconnected system. 1.6.1 The facilities and/or protective relay systems shall be designed to fit into the electrical system configuration and shall be acceptable to the Parties. 1.6.2 Transmission Owner and Interconnection Customer agree that each shall give a 90-day advance notice to the other Party of any such additions which it may contemplate making so as to attain the best practicable coordination of future system plans and the design of any necessary facilities. 1.7 Payments Any payments arising from projects associated with this Agreement will be negotiated and memorialized in a separate, specific Agreement. Details pertaining to those payments will be documented in that Agreement. For any payments arising from this Agreement and not memorialized in a separate agreement: 1.7.1 All payments to Transmission Owner shall be made payable to ITC Midwest, LLC, and shall be sent to: ITC Midwest, LLC PO Box 673971 Detroit, MI 48267-3971 or by wire transfer to a bank designated by Transmission Owner. 1.7.2 All payments to Interconnection Customer shall be made payable to the Interconnection customer and shall be sent to: Maquoketa Municipal Electric Utility 201 East Pleasant Street Maquoketa, IA 52060 or by wire transfer to a bank designated by Interconnection Customer.
1.7.3 Invoices shall be due 30 days from the date the invoice is issued. Any invoice payment not made on or before the due date shall bear interest, from the due date until the date upon which payment is made, at an annual percent rate of interest equal to the lesser of (a) the prime rate published by the Wall Street Journal on the due date, plus (2%), or (b) the highest rate permitted by law. SECTION 2. DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION OF THE CONNECTION FACILITIES 2.1 Authority for Interconnection Customer Construction Except as provided in the subsection 2.1.1, Interconnection Customer shall have sole authority to manage, design, supervise, construct, procure materials for, control and take all steps which it deems necessary or appropriate for the installation of the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities required pursuant to Subsection 1.2, “Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities”. 2.1.1 The design, specifications, installation and construction of the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities required pursuant to Subsection 1.2, shall be in accordance with Good Utility Practice as defined in Section 3.1, and compatible with standards used by the Transmission Owner for its own installations at similar voltages. 2.1.2 The design and specifications of any new Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities required pursuant to Subsection 1.2 shall be subject to the inspection of and comment by Transmission Owner prior to being placed into operation. However, Transmission Owner shall have no obligation or responsibility with respect to such design, plans, specifications, installation or construction because of its inspection and comment thereon. 2.1.3 Transmission Owner shall connect to Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities if, and only if, the specifications, design, installation and construction of Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities are in accordance with Good Utility Practice as defined in Section 3.1 and compatible with standards used by the Transmission Owner for its own installations at similar voltages. 2.2 Authority for Transmission Owner Construction Transmission Owner shall have sole authority to manage, design, supervise, construct, procure materials for, control and shall take all steps which it deems necessary or appropriate for the installation and connection of its Transmission Owner Connection Facilities required pursuant to Subsection 1.3, “Transmission Owner Connection Facilities” in accordance with Good Utility Practice as defined in Section 3.1.
SECTION 3. OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE 3.1 Operation and Maintenance by Transmission Owner Transmission Owner (a) shall have sole authority and responsibility to operate and maintain Transmission Owner Connection Facilities required pursuant to Subsection 1.3 in accordance with “Good Utility Practice”, and (b) may perform emergency maintenance, or make system modifications, when necessary, on the Transmission Owner Connection Facilities. Good Utility Practice means any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, including compliance with FERC-approved Reliability Standards of the North American Electric Reliability Corporation, or its successor organization, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather intended to include acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region, including those practices required by Federal Power Act Section 215(a)(4). 3.2 Operation and Maintenance by Interconnection Customer Interconnection Customer shall have sole authority and responsibility to operate and maintain the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities required pursuant to Subsection 1.2 in accordance with Good Utility Practice. Should the Interconnection Customer fail to maintain its equipment according to Good Utility Practice, the Transmission Owner shall notify the Interconnection Customer of such and shall have sole authority to either disconnect the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities until such time maintenance work is completed or to perform the necessary maintenance work at the Interconnection Customer’s expense. 3.3 Insurance 3.3.1 Interconnection Customer shall acquire and maintain property insurance on the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities. 3.3.2 Transmission Owner shall acquire and maintain property insurance on the Transmission Owner Connection Facilities. 3.3.3 Commercial general liability insurance as such insurance relates to the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities and to the site upon which the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities are to be located shall be maintained by the Interconnection Customer.. Such insurance policy shall name the Transmission Owner as an additional insured. Upon request of the Transmission Owner, the Interconnection Customer shall deliver a certificate of insurance as it relates to this Agreement.
3.3.4 Commercial general liability insurance as such insurance relates to the Transmission Owner Connection Facilities and to the site upon which the Transmission Owner Connection Facilities are to be located shall be maintained by the Transmission Owner. Such insurance policy shall name the Interconnection Customer as an additional insured. Upon request of the Interconnection Customer, the Transmission Owner shall deliver a certificate of insurance as it relates to this Agreement. 3.4 Taxes 3.4.1 Any applicable taxes or assessments levied or incurred as a result of the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities or business activities, shall be the responsibility of the Interconnection Customer. The Interconnection Customer shall indemnify and hold harmless the Transmission Owner on account of any such taxes and assessments. Taxes include, but are not limited to, applicable real and personal property taxes. If Interconnection Customer’s payment for any work under the Agreement constitutes a Contribution in Aid of Construction Agreement (CIAC), the tax obligation will include a gross-up based on the current annual tax rate. The tax gross-up will be calculated using the following method: Current Tax Rate x (Gross Income Amount – Present Value Depreciation Amount) / (1 – Current Tax Rate). While the estimate will be intended to cover the entire tax obligation, Interconnection Customer agrees to reimburse Transmission Owner for such additional taxes, including penalty and interest payments, if any, imposed by the Internal Revenue Service or other taxing authority with jurisdiction over any work within thirty (30) days of notice provided by ITC Midwest of such tax obligation. 3.4.2 Any applicable taxes or assessments levied or incurred as a result of the Transmission Owner Connection Facilities or business activities shall be the responsibility of the Transmission Owner. The Transmission Owner shall indemnify and hold harmless the Interconnection Customer on account of any such taxes and assessment. Taxes include, but are not limited to, applicable real and property taxes. 3.5 Environmental Safety Each Party agrees to construct, maintain and operate its respective Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities or Transmission Owner Connection Facilities so as not to create or exacerbate any environmental hazard or risk. If a Party creates an environmental hazard at the site, that Party agrees to promptly and at its sole expense remediate the hazard and be responsible for all due care activities. SECTION 4. CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION 4.1 "Confidential Information"
Confidential information includes, but is not limited to, technical information, information about product plans and strategies, promotions, customers and related technical, Critical Energy Infrastructure Information (”CEII”), Confidential Records as that term is defined in Iowa Code Section 22.7(50), financial or business information which the disclosing Party (the "Disclosing Party") considers to be the confidential information of the Disclosing Party or its third party contractors, licensors or suppliers. Confidential Information shall be (a) written information received from the Disclosing Party which is marked or identified as confidential; or (b) oral or visual (or other non-tangible format) information identified as confidential at the time of disclosure which is summarized in writing to the receiving Party (the “Receiving Party”) promptly after such disclosure; or (c) information which a reasonable person under the circumstances would know the Disclosing Party intended to be treated as Confidential Information. 4.2 Protection of Confidential Information The Receiving Party shall use the same degree of care that it uses to protect the confidentiality of its own confidential information of like kind (but in no event less than reasonable care) (a) not to use any Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party for any purpose outside the scope of this Agreement, and (b) except as otherwise authorized by the Disclosing Party in writing, to limit access to Confidential Information or CEII of the Disclosing Party to those of its, and its affiliates, employees, consultants, contractors and agents who need such access for purposes consistent with this Agreement and who have signed confidentiality agreements with the Receiving Party containing protections of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information or CEII. Each of the Parties will be responsible for the actions of its affiliates and their respective employees, consultants, contractors and agents in violation of this Section 4. 4.3 Exceptions 4.3.1 The confidentiality obligations will not extend to information that: (a) was already known by or available to the Receiving Party without obligation of confidentiality prior to disclosure under this Agreement; (b) is or becomes publicly known without breach by the Receiving Party; (c) is rightfully received by the Receiving Party from a third party without a duty of confidentiality; (d) is independently developed or learned by the Receiving Party without use of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information; (e) is disclosed by the Receiving Party with the Disclosing Party’s prior written approval, or (f) is required to be disclosed pursuant to a lawful order of a governmental authority, so long as the Party required to disclose the information provides the Party owning such Confidential Information with timely prior notice of such requirement and provided that such information will remain confidential for all other purposes under this Agreement. 4.3.2 Transmission Owner recognizes and acknowledges that Interconnection Customer and the City of Maquoketa, Iowa (the “City”) are public bodies as defined under the Iowa Open Records Act, Iowa Code Chapter 22 (the “IORA”) and that, with the exception of Confidential Records which have been clearly identified or
labeled as “Critical Energy Infrastructure Information,” “Critical Physical Infrastructure Information,” or “Critical Infrastructure Information” in compliance with Iowa Code Section 22.7(5), other records of the Parties including, but not limited to, this Interconnection Agreement, may be deemed public records as defined in the IORA. Nothing in this Interconnection Agreement shall be construed as protecting any of the public record of the Interconnection Customer or the City from public disclosure as required under the IORA. 4.4 Remedies Regarding Confidentiality The Parties agree that monetary damages by themselves will be inadequate to compensate a Party for the other Party’s breach of its obligations under this Section 4. Each Party accordingly agrees that the other Party is entitled to adequate relief, by way of injunction or otherwise, if it breaches its obligation under this Section. SECTION 5. SERVICE CONDITIONS 5.1 Reactive Control 5.1.1 Transmission Owner and Interconnection Customer recognize and further agree that Interconnection Customer and Transmission Owner have a mutual responsibility for maintaining voltage at each Interconnection Point, in accordance with Good Utility Practice, the requirements herein and any applicable reliability standards. (i) Interconnection Customer shall maintain a system average power factor of at least 98% leading or lagging, as measured at the distribution side of the Interconnection Point(s), at load levels greater than 90% of the Interconnection Customer’s monthly system peak load. (ii) Interconnection Customer shall maintain a system average power factor between 90% leading and 90% lagging, as measured at the distribution side of the Interconnection Point(s). (iii) The Transmission Owner shall have the ability to request the Interconnection Customer to correct power factor(s) at delivery points in an area or region requiring reactive support. Upon request by Transmission Owner, Interconnection Customer shall use reasonable efforts to correct power factor in a timely fashion. (iv) Transmission Owner recognizes that there may be situations where power factor correction is best accomplished on the Transmission System. The Transmission Owner shall use reasonable efforts to make appropriate changes to the system to compensate for reactive power losses.
(v) The Parties agree to cooperate in the installation and management of reactive power resources connected to their respective systems. 5.2 Continuity of Service Each Party shall exercise reasonable care to maintain continuity of service over its facilities as provided under this Agreement. If continuity of service becomes interrupted for scheduled and unscheduled outages, maintenance, shutdowns or any reason (collectively, “interruption of service”) the cause of the interruption of service shall be removed as soon as practicable and normal operating conditions shall be restored. Neither Party shall be responsible to the other Party for any damage or loss of revenue or other liability, damage or expense of any kind whatsoever, caused by or resulting from or in connection with any interruption of service. Settlement of strikes and labor disturbances shall be wholly within the discretion of the Party having such difficulty. 5.3 Transmission Service Transmission Owner makes no representations to Interconnection Customer regarding the availability of transmission service, and Interconnection Customer agrees that the availability of transmission service may not be inferred or implied from Transmission Owner's execution of this Agreement. Interconnection Customer, or its designated agent, must request such service in accordance with the provisions of the MISO Tariff. Interconnection Customer, or its designated agent, must maintain transmission service for the duration of the Agreement, and must demonstrate its compliance with this requirement, if requested by Transmission Owner. 5.4 Access Rights Upon reasonable notice, each Party (a) shall furnish at no cost to the other Party any rights of use, licenses, rights of way and easements with respect to lands owned or controlled by the furnishing Party that are necessary to enable the other Party to obtain ingress and egress to construct, reconstruct, operate, maintain, repair, test (or witness testing), inspect, replace or remove facilities and equipment to: (i) interconnect the Transmission Owners Connection Facilities and Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities; (ii) operate and maintain the Transmission Owner Connection Facilities and the Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities; and (iii) disconnect or remove the other Party’s facilities and equipment upon termination of this Agreement, and (b) shall grant to the other Party any necessary easements in a form that is acceptable to the other Party. 5.5 NERC Responsibilities Transmission Owner, as the NERC-registered Transmission Operator, has the authority, as described in NERC’s Reliability Standards, to issue directives to Interconnection Customer to ensure the reliability of the Bulk Electric System. These directives may include, but are not limited to: a) changes in a generator’s real or reactive output; and b) the shedding of firm load.
SECTION 6. INDEMNITY; LIMITATION ON LIABILITY; FORCE MAJEIJRE 6.1 Indemnity To the fullest extent permitted by law, each Party shall at all times assume all liability for, and shall indemnify and save the other Party and its trustees, officers, directors, employees, affiliate companies, and agents harmless from, any and all damages, losses, claims, demands, suits, recoveries, costs, legal fees, and expenses for injury to or death of any person or persons whomsoever occurring on its own system, or for any loss, destruction of or damage to any property of third persons, firms, corporations or other entities occurring on its own system, arising out of or resulting from, either directly or indirectly, its own facilities, or arising out of or resulting from, either directly or indirectly, any electric energy furnished to it after such energy has been delivered to it by such other Party, unless caused by the sole negligence or intentional wrongdoing of the other Party, its trustees, officers, directors, employees, agents, or invitees. 6.2 Limitation on Liability NEITHER PARTY SHALL IN ANY EVENT BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER FOR ANY SPECIAL, INCIDENTAL, EXEMPLARY, PUNITIVE OR CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES SUCH AS, BUT NOT LIMITED TO, LOST PROFITS, REVENUE OR GOODWILL, INTEREST, LOSS BY REASON OF SHUTDOWN OR NON-OPERATION OF EQUIPMENT OR MACHINERY, INCREASED EXPENSE OF OPERATION OF EQUIPMENT OR MACHINERY, COST OF PURCHASED OR REPLACEMENT POWER OR SERVICES OR CLAIMS BY CUSTOMERS, WHETHER SUCH LOSS IS BASED ON CONTRACT, WARRANTY, NEGLIGENCE, STRICT LIABILITY OR OTHERWISE, EVEN IF THE PARTY HAS BEEN ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGES. THIS SECTION 6.2 SHALL NOT APPLY TO OR AFFECT THE PARTIES’ OBLIGATIONS FOR INDEMNIFICATION AS SET FORTH IN SECTION 6.1. 6.3 Force Majeure IN NO EVENT SHALL EITHER PARTY BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER PARTY FOR ANY ACT, OMISSION OR CIRCUMSTANCE OCCASIONED BY OR IN CONSEQUENCE OF ANY ACT OF GOD, LABOR DISTURBANCE, ACT OF THE PUBLIC ENEMY, WAR, INSURRECTION, RIOT, FIRE, STORM OR FLOOD, EXPLOSION, BREAKAGE OR ACCIDENT TO MACHINERY OR EQUIPMENT, CURTAILMENT, ORDER, REGULATION OR RESTRICTION IMPOSED BY GOVERNMENTAL, MILITARY OR LAWFULLY ESTABLISHED CIVILIAN AUTHORITIES OR BY THE MAKING OF NECESSARY REPAIRS UPON THE PROPERTY OR EQUIPMENT OF EITHER PARTY, OR BY ANY OTHER CAUSE OR CAUSES BEYOND EITHER PARTY’S REASONABLE CONTROL. NEITHER PARTY SHALL BE REQUIRED TO SETTLE ANY STRIKE OR OTHER LABOR
PROBLEM IN A MANNER NOT COMPLETELY SATISFACTORY TO IT. SECTION 7. SUCCESSORS AND ASSIGNS 7.1 Binding Effect This Agreement shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the successors and assigns of the respective Parties. 7.2 Assignment Neither Party shall assign, transfer or otherwise alienate its interest in this Agreement in whole or in part without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld. Any attempted assignment without securing the consent of the other Party shall be null and void, and of no force and effect. SECTION 8. NOTICE TO PARTIES Unless otherwise provided in this Agreement, any notice, consent or other communication required to be made under this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be mailed by first class US mail, postage prepaid or delivered to the address set forth below or such other address as the receiving Party may designate in writing. ITC Midwest, LLC 27175 Energy Way Novi, MI 48377 Attention: V.P. & General Counsel – Utility Operations Maquoketa Municipal Electric Utility 201 East Pleasant Street Maquoketa, IA 52060 Attention: Chris Krogman, General Manager All notices shall be effective when received. For questions and concerns of Emergency Operations contact, as applicable, MISO or the Transmission Owner Operations Control Room per the Transmission Owner - Interconnection Customer Operating Procedure, a copy of which has been provided to Interconnection Customer. SECTION 9. GOVERNING LAW This Agreement shall be deemed to be an Iowa contract and shall be construed in accordance with and governed by the laws of Iowa, exclusive of its conflict of laws principles.
SECTION 10. REGULATORY APPROVAL This Agreement will be filed with Federal Energy Regulatory Commission for approval under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act as soon as practicable after its execution by the Parties. The Parties agree to support such filing, to reasonably cooperate with respect to the filing, and to provide any information, including the filing of testimony, reasonably required to comply with applicable filing requirement. SECTION 11. EFFECTIVE DATE, TERM AND TERMINATION This Agreement shall be effective when accepted or ordered by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and shall continue in full force and effect so long as any Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities are connected to Transmission Owner Connection Facilities for transmission service, except that it may be terminated by mutual agreement of the Parties and upon not less than 24 months written notice given by either of the Parties. SECTION 12. RETIREMENT At such time as the interconnection is no longer required, the retirement of the facilities comprising the Interconnection shall be the responsibility of the Party owning such facilities. The retirement and removal of facilities shall be done as expeditiously as possible. SECTION 13. ENTIRE AGREEMENT, THIRD PARTIES AND AMENDMENTS This Agreement supersedes all previous representations, understandings, negotiations and agreements either written or oral between the Parties or their representatives and constitutes the entire agreement of the Parties about the Interconnection. This Agreement is intended for the benefit of the Parties only and does not grant any rights to any third parties unless otherwise specifically stated. No amendments or changes to this Agreement shall be binding unless made in writing and duly executed by both Parties. SECTION 14. MASTER JOINT USE POLE AGREEMENT FOR DISTRIBUTION UNDERBUILD BETWEEN ITC MIDWEST LLC AND MUNICIPALITY THIS JOINT USE POLE AGREEMENT FOR DISTRIBUTION UNDERBUILD (“Agreement”) is made by and between ITC Midwest LLC, a Michigan limited liability company with its primary office at 27175 Energy Way, Novi, MI 48377 (“ITC”) and MAQUOKETA MUNICIPAL ELECTRIC UTILITY with its principal office at 201 East Pleasant Street, Maquoketa, Iowa 52060 (“MUNICIPALITY”). ITC and MUNICIPALITY may be referred to herein individually as a “Party” and collectively as the “Parties.” WITNESSETH: WHEREAS, ITC owns and operates an electric transmission system, including pole structures associated with the transmission of electricity; and WHEREAS, MUNICIPALITY owns and operates an electric transmission and distribution system; and WHEREAS, this Agreement is executed in anticipation and support of consummation of a certain transaction between the Parties whereby ITC will purchase the transmission assets of MUNICIPALITY (the “Transaction”), after which Transaction portions of MUNICIPALITY’s electric distribution system will remain attached to transmission pole structures owned by ITC (more fully defined hereinafter as the “Joint Use Poles”); and WHEREAS, ITC is willing to allow MUNICIPALITY to retain its existing distribution attachments if any, and permit MUNICIPALITY to make future attachments to ITC pole structures, subject to the terms and conditions herein contained; and WHEREAS, the Parties wish to set forth certain understandings with respect to the current and future, if any, attachments to the Joint Use Poles; and NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the promises and mutual covenants hereinafter contained, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: DEFINITIONS 1. Definitions: For the purposes of this Agreement the following definitions apply: “MUNICIPALITY Facilities” shall mean all existing and future MUNICIPALITY-owned Facilities. “Facilities” shall mean facilities attached to the Joint Use Poles, including but not limited to insulators, arms, conductors, shield wires, circuits and all other equipment or hardware used in a Party’s operation of its distribution or transmission system, and any equipment or hardware required to attach the same to the Joint Use Poles. “Good Utility Practice” shall mean any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be acceptable practices, methods or acts generally accepted in the region. “ITC Facilities” shall mean all existing and future ITC-owned Facilities, as defined above. “Joint Use Poles” shall mean any existing and all future pole structures and foundations owned by ITC that support both ITC Facilities and MUNICIPALITY Facilities, and specifically excludes pole structures owned solely by MUNICIPALITY. “Work” shall mean and encompass all line design, construction, reconstruction, relocation, repair, replacement, maintenance and operation on, to, or of MUNICIPALITY Facilities, ITC Facilities or Joint Use Poles as the case and context may be herein. EFFECTIVE DATE AND APPLICATION 2. Effective Date. This Agreement shall become effective upon the date this Agreement is accepted by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) or upon a date specified by the FERC (the “Effective Date”) or upon consummation of the Transaction, whichever is later, and shall continue in effect subject to the terms hereof. 3. Application of Agreement. This Agreement shall apply to all Joint Use Poles and includes existing Joint Use Poles for which the Parties do not have an existing agreement, supersedes and replaces any current common use agreements dated prior to the Effective Date hereof, and all future Joint Use Poles. ATTACHMENT PROCESS GENERALLY 4. Process for Attachment. The following process applies to the attachment of MUNICIPALITY Facilities to ITC pole structures: (a) Request Process. As described in this Agreement where MUNICIPALITY needs or desires to attach new attachments to ITC pole structures, or upgraded Facilities (other than mere replacement of like kind) on Joint Use Poles, MUNICIPALITY shall send ITC a request using a pole attachment request form or a load interconnection form, as appropriate, located on ITC’s website (a “Request”) for ITC’s review. ITC’s approval of MUNICIPALITY’s Request shall not be unreasonably withheld or denied. The Request shall be used for each and every incident of attachment to ITC pole structures. (b) Denial. A Request may be denied for reasons, including but not limited to: safety, reliability, regulatory requirements, conflicting contractual obligations or franchise requirements, restrictions in easements or other land rights, guying considerations, ITC policies and standards or generally applicable engineering reasons, including transmission 2 system security and operability or structural integrity and/or capability of the Joint Use Poles and voltage levels. Generally, most requests to attach to pole structures upon which ITC has Facilities that operate at voltage levels greater than 100kV will be denied. (c) Approval. Upon ITC’s approval of a Request MUNICIPALITY may attach or cause to be attached the MUNICIPALITY Facilities to ITC pole structures in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. NEW ATTACHMENTS TO EXISTING ITC POLE STRUCTURES AND REPLACEMENT ATTACHMENTS ON EXISTING JOINT USE POLES NOT AS PART OF AN ITC REBUILD/REPLACEMENT PROJECT 5. Party Obligations in Circumstances of Attachment of MUNICIPALITY’s New Facilities on ITC’s Existing Pole Structures or Replacement Facilities on Existing Joint Use Poles Not the Subject of an ITC Rebuild or Replacement Project. (a) Payment. When considering a Request for new attachments of MUNICIPALITY Facilities on existing pole structures or replacement attachments of MUNICIPALITY Facilities on existing Joint Use Poles that are not part of an ITC rebuild or replacement project if, in ITC’s sole discretion, the pole structure or Joint Use Pole is inadequate to support the additional load, or rearrangement or relocation of facilities is necessary, ITC shall communicate any necessary changes to MUNICIPALITY and the estimated costs. If MUNICIPALITY elects to continue with the attachments of MUNICIPALITY Facilities, MUNICIPALITY shall bear the costs in accordance with the payment terms set forth in Section 10. (a) Pole Support. It is anticipated that any strengthening or guying of ITC pole structures or Joint Use Poles that is required to accommodate MUNICIPALITY Facilities will be provided at the expense of MUNICIPALITY. In the event that ITC completes any necessary strengthening or guying required to accommodate MUNICIPALITY Facilities, ITC may charge the expense to MUNICIPALITY. (b) MUNICIPALITY’s Rights of Way, Permits, Approvals. Upon ITC’s approval of MUNICIPALITY’s Request, MUNICIPALITY shall, at its sole expense, procure and maintain any and all easements, licenses, consents, franchises, certificates of approval and permits for the proposed attachment of MUNICIPALITY Facilities that may be required by any property owners or that may be required to be in the name of MUNICIPALITY as required by any municipal, state and other governmental authorities having jurisdiction. NEW AND REPLACEMENT ATTACHMENTS ON EXISTING JOINT USE POLES AS PART OF AN ITC-INITIATED REBUILD/REPLACEMENT PROJECT OR ITC OVERTAKING MUNICIPALITY’S EXISTING ROUTE 6. Party Obligations During an ITC-Initiated Rebuild or Replacement Project on Existing Joint Use Poles or ITC Overtaking MUNICIPALITY’S Existing Route. MUNICIPALITY Facilities may need to be removed and reinstalled or removed and replaced in the event ITC seeks to rebuild or replace existing Joint Use Poles or in the event ITC seeks to overtake an existing line route operated by MUNICIPALITY. In such events: 3 (a) Performance. ITC shall install, or cause to be installed, the Joint Use Poles, and ITC’s Facilities. ITC will be responsible for and assume the costs of the removal and installation of MUNICIPALITY’s Facilities or any replacement MUNICIPALITY Facilities. If MUNICIPALITY desires new MUNICIPALITY Facilities to be installed in place of those being removed, MUNICIPALITY shall be responsible to pay for and supply all MUNICIPALITY’s Facilities and materials. If any such new MUNICIPALITY Facilities are greater in quantity or size which, in ITC’s discretion, requires additional labor by ITC in addition to that which would already be provided or necessitating new or different pole structures other than ITC’s contemplated structure design, then ITC shall communicate the flat fee per pole structure labor cost and/or flat fee pole structure material cost to MUNICIPALITY and, if MUNICIPALITY elects to proceed with the new MUNICIPALITY Facilities, MUNICIPALITY shall make payment in accordance with Section 11. (b) Easements: No Warranties or Guarantees; MUNICIPALITY Indemnification. ITC will procure and maintain any and all easements or other land rights that are necessary for ITC’s pole structures and ITC Facilities. If obtaining new easements, ITC will use reasonable efforts to negotiate easements which provide ITC the ability to extend the right to jointly use the easement with other parties. ITC hereby disclaims and makes no representation(s) to MUNICIPALITY with respect to the rights of attachment obtained, including the adequacy or sufficiency of rights acquired from and granted by third parties for MUNICIPALITY’s Facilities attachment(s). To be clear, ITC makes no guarantees or assurances that it will be successful in negotiating easements that allow for ITC to extend the right to jointly use with MUNICIPALITY, and in the event ITC is unsuccessful it shall be the MUNICIPALITY’s responsibility to obtain any and all rights necessary to co-locate MUNICIPALITY Facilities on ITC facilities. To the extent MUNICIPALITY is able, in ITC’s sole determination, to rely on land rights owned by ITC, MUNICIPALITY shall not exceed the scope of any ITC easement, or other applicable agreement with a landowner. To the extent ITC is able, and the Parties agree, ITC may procure land rights from those rights owned by MUNICIPALITY. In such a case, ITC shall not exceed the scope of any MUNICIPALITY easement, or other applicable agreement with a landowner. In such an event those rights from the MUNICIPALITY are inadequate for ITC’s use, ITC shall procure and maintain any additional easements or other land rights that are necessary. MUNICIPALITY shall indemnify ITC for any claims, losses, damages, costs attorneys’ fees and/or expenses arising from MUNICIPALITY’s unauthorized use of the Joint Use Poles without the required easement or land rights. Likewise, to the extent that ITC does rely upon an easement of MUNICIPALITY, ITC shall indemnify MUNICIPALITY for any claims, losses, damages, costs, attorneys’ fees and/or expenses arising from ITC exceeding the scope of such MUNICIPALITY easement. ATTACHMENT TO ITC POLE STRUCTURES DURING ITC-INITIATED REBUILD/REPLACEMENT PROJECTS WHERE MUNICIPALITY DOES NOT HAVE EXISTING FACILITIES 7. Party Obligations During ITC New Or Rebuild Projects Where MUNICIPALITY Does Not Have Existing Facilities. If MUNICIPALITY desires to install MUNICIPALITY Facilities on ITC pole structures during a new ITC line project or rebuild project where 4 MUNICIPALITY does not have existing MUNICIPALITY Facilities, the following shall apply: (a) Performance. ITC shall install, or cause to be installed, the pole structures and ITC Facilities. MUNICIPALITY will be responsible for and assume the costs of supplying MUNICIPALITY Facilities and related materials and the installation of MUNICIPALITY’S Facilities. In the event ITC installs MUNICIPALITY’s Facilities, payment terms shall be in accordance with Section 13. (b) Pole Support. It is anticipated that any strengthening or guying of ITC pole structures or Joint Use Poles required to accommodate MUNICIPALITY Facilities will be provided at the expense of MUNICIPALITY. In the event that ITC completes any necessary strengthening or guying required to accommodate MUNICIPALITY Facilities, ITC may charge the expense to MUNICIPALITY. (c) Easements: No Warranties or Guarantees; MUNICIPALITY Indemnification. ITC will procure and maintain any and all easements or other land rights that are necessary for ITC’s pole structures and Facilities. If MUNICIPALITY makes its Request prior to the time that ITC has acquired its rights of way/easements, ITC will, without obligation to MUNICIPALITY, use reasonable efforts to negotiate easements which provide ITC the ability to extend the right to jointly use the easement with other parties. To be clear, ITC makes no guarantees or assurances that it will be successful in negotiating easements that allow for ITC to extend the right to jointly use with MUNICIPALITY and, in the event ITC is unsuccessful, it shall be the MUNICIPALITY’s responsibility to obtain any and all rights necessary to co-locate on ITC facilities. ITC hereby disclaims and makes no representation(s) to MUNICIPALITY with respect to the rights of attachment obtained, including the adequacy or sufficiency of rights acquired from and granted by third parties for MUNICIPALITY’s Facilities and attachment(s). To the extent MUNICIPALITY relies on land rights owned by ITC, MUNICIPALITY shall not exceed the scope of any ITC easement, or other applicable agreement with a landowner. MUNICIPALITY shall indemnify ITC for any claims, losses, damages, costs, attorneys’ fees and/or expenses arising from MUNICIPALITY’s unauthorized use of the Joint Use Poles without the required easement or land rights. (d) MUNICIPALITY’s Rights of Way, Permits, Approvals. Upon ITC’s approval of MUNICIPALITY’s Request, MUNICIPALITY shall determine with ITC whether easement/rights of way have been acquired to accommodate MUNICIPALITY’S Facilities and, if not, MUNICIPALITY shall coordinate efforts to obtain such rights. In the event and to the extent that ITC has obtained easement rights that do not accommodate MUNICIPALITY Facilities, MUNICIPALITY shall, at its sole expense, procure and maintain any and all easements, licenses or consents that are necessary for MUNICIPALITY Facilities and not obtained by ITC. MUNICIPALITY shall further, at its sole expense, procure and maintain any necessary franchises, certificates of approval and permits for the proposed MUNICIPALITY Facilities and attachment that may be required by any property owners or that may be required to be in the name of MUNICIPALITY as required by any municipal, state and other governmental authorities having jurisdiction. FORCED RELOCATION OF JOINT USE POLES BY THIRD PARTY 8. Party Obligations During Forced Relocation of Joint Use Poles by a Third Party. 5 MUNICIPALITY Facilities may need to be relocated in the event of forced relocation. In such events: (a) Performance. ITC shall relocate, or cause to be relocated, the Joint Use Poles, and ITC Facilities. MUNICIPALITY will be responsible for and assume the costs of the removal and reconnection of existing MUNICIPALITY Facilities, or the removal and installation of any new replacement MUNICIPALITY Facilities, to the extent that MUNICIPALITY or ITC is not reimbursed by the public authority and/or under an applicable regulation for the removal and installation of MUNICIPALITY Facilities. To the extent ITC performs the removal and installation of MUNICIPALITY Facilities for which ITC is not reimbursed by the public authority and/or under an applicable regulation, MUNICIPALITY shall make payment to ITC in accordance with the terms in Section 10. MUNICIPALITY shall be responsible to pay for and supply all MUNICIPALITY Facilities. (b) Easements: No Warranties or Guarantees; MUNICIPALITY Indemnification. ITC will procure and maintain any and all easements or other land rights that are necessary for ITC’s pole structures and Facilities. If obtaining new easements, ITC may, at its option and without obligation to MUNICIPALITY, use efforts to negotiate easements which provide ITC the ability to extend the right to jointly use the easement with other parties. To be clear, ITC makes no guarantees or assurances that it will be successful in negotiating easements that allow for ITC to extend the right to jointly use with MUNICIPALITY, and in the event ITC is unsuccessful it shall be the MUNICIPALITY’s responsibility to obtain any and all rights necessary to co-locate MUNICIPALITY Facilities on ITC facilities. ITC hereby disclaims and makes no representation(s) to MUNICIPALITY with respect to the rights of attachment obtained, including the adequacy or sufficiency of rights acquired from and granted by third parties for MUNICIPALITY Facilities. To the extent MUNICIPALITY relies on land rights owned by ITC, MUNICIPALITY shall not exceed the scope of any ITC easement, or other applicable agreement with a landowner. To the extent ITC is able, and the Parties agree, ITC may procure land rights from those rights owned by MUNICIPALITY. In such a case, ITC shall not exceed the scope of any MUNICIPALITY easement, or other applicable agreement with a landowner. In such an event those rights from the MUNICIPALITY are inadequate for ITC’s use, ITC shall procure and maintain any additional easements or other land rights that are necessary. MUNICIPALITY shall indemnify ITC for any claims, losses, damages, costs attorneys’ fees and/or expenses arising from MUNICIPALITY’s unauthorized use of the Joint Use Poles without the required easement or land rights. Likewise, to the extent that ITC does rely upon an easement of MUNICIPALITY, ITC shall indemnify MUNICIPALITY for any claims, losses, damages, costs, attorneys’ fees and/or expenses arising from ITC exceeding the scope of such MUNICIPALITY easement. ATTACHMENT OPTIONS DURING ITC-INITIATED PROJECTS WHEN ITC AND MUNICIPALITY OCCUPY SAME RIGHT-OF-WAY 9. Party Obligations During ITC Rebuild Project When ITC and MUNICIPALITY Occupy Same Right-Of-Way. MUNICIPALITY Facilities may need to be relocated in the event ITC 6 rebuilds or replaces ITC Facilities and MUNICIPALITY has an existing line in the same right-of-way but the Parties are not located on ITC pole structures. In such events: (a) Option to Opt Out. If MUNICIPALITY does not wish to be transferred onto ITC pole structures, MUNICIPALITY shall submit to ITC a letter requesting, for good cause, that the MUNICIPALITY Facilities not be relocated to the new ITC pole structures. ITC will then request that the Iowa Utility Board authorize separate pole lines based on MUNICIPALITY’S request. (b) Performance. If MUNICIPALITY seeks to transfer its line onto ITC pole structures, the terms of Section 6 shall apply in its entirety. PAYMENT FOR NEW ATTACHMENTS TO EXISTING ITC POLE STRUCTURES AND REPLACEMENT ATTACHMENTS ON EXISTING JOINT USE POLES NOT PART OF AN ITC REBUILD/REPLACEMENT PROJECT 10. Payment Terms. If in ITC’s discretion the ITC pole structure(s) or Joint Use Pole(s) is inadequate to support the additional load, or rearrangement or relocation of MUNICIPALITY Facilities is necessary, or betterment costs are triggered due to an increase in quantity and/or size of MUNICIPALITY Facilities on the pole structures or Joint Use Poles, then MUNICIPALITY shall bear the costs in accordance with the following payment terms: (a) MUNICIPALITY shall pay ITC for the cost of the work to be performed at the project, which shall include the cost of all labor, overhead, rental costs, fees, design, permitting, administrative and engineering costs, taxes and the cost of materials and equipment used to complete the project. (b) ITC will send MUNICIPALITY an estimate of the cost of the work to be performed at the project (the “Projected Cost”). MUNICIPALITY’s payment of the Projected Cost is due to ITC in advance of any work performed by ITC. (c) ITC shall have one hundred eighty days (180) following the completion of the work to perform a reconciliation of the actual cost of performance and the Projected Cost. To the extent the actual cost of performance is less than the Projected Cost paid by MUNICIPALITY, ITC will refund the excess funds to MUNICIPALITY within thirty (30) days of the reconciliation. If the actual cost exceeds the Projected Cost paid by MUNICIPALITY, MUNICIPALITY shall pay ITC the balance of the actual cost within thirty (30) days of receipt of an invoice from ITC. (d) MUNICIPALITY’s payment may be classified as a Contribution In Aid of Construction (“CIAC”) payment, which is intended to cover the full cost of performance of the project. If classified as a CIAC, the Projected Cost will include a gross-up based on ITC’s then current annual tax rate. While the estimate is intended to cover the entire tax obligation, MUNICIPALITY agrees to reimburse ITC for such additional taxes, including penalty and interest payments, if any, imposed by the Internal Revenue Service or other taxing authority with jurisdiction over the Project within thirty (30) days of notice provided 7 by ITC of such tax obligation. PAYMENT FOR ADDITIONAL LABOR AND/OR LARGER STRUCTURES 11. Payment Terms. If MUNICIPALITY Facilities are increased in size or quantity resulting in either or both: i) labor by ITC in addition to that which would already be provided under the circumstances and/or ii) the need for modified or new pole structures other than ITC’s contemplated structure design then ITC may charge MUNICIPALITY a flat fee per pole structure labor cost and/or a flat fee per pole structure material cost for each structure upon which MUNICIPALITY seeks to attach such MUNICIPALITY Facilities. (a) Within a reasonable time of ITC’s notice of the increased size or quantity of MUNICIPALITY Facilities, ITC shall notify MUNICIPALITY of any such per pole structure labor cost and/or a flat fee per pole structure material costs in advance and, if MUNICIPALITY elects to proceed, ITC will invoice MUNICIPALITY in advance of performance of such work allowing ten (10) days for payment of such cost or such other time, more or less, as may be required by the work performance schedule. SECTION 1. CONNECTION FACILITIES
1.1 General

associated appurtenances which will be used in the connection of the Interconnection
Customer’s distribution substations or facilities to the Transmission Owner’s electric
transmission system.

Facilities”.

Customer’s system; (ii) Federal, state or local laws, regulations or codes; or (iii)
design or operation of Transmission Owner’s system, later necessitate additional
facilities or modifications to the then existing Connection Facilities herein, the

modification of Connection Facilities that directly impacts the other Party such

including modifications to operations of the Connection Facilities, shall only be
allowed if mutually agreed to by the Parties.
1.1.3.1 Before undertaking such future additions or modifications, the
Parties shall consult, develop plans and coordinate schedules of activities.
1.1.3.2 The cost of such future additions or modifications to the
Interconnection Customer Connection Facilities shall be borne by the

cost is approved or required by the appropriate regulatory agency to be
assigned to Interconnection Customer; or such future additions or
modifications are requested by the Interconnection Customer and such

responsibilities for any such future additions or modifications shall be
made consistent with the responsibilities allocated in this Agreement.

Connection Facilities as described in Appendix A1. In addition to the Interconnection
Customer Connection Facilities described in Appendix A1, the Interconnection Customer

Connection Facilities:1.2.1 Interconnection billing and load control metering equipment which is
compliant with MISO and Local Balancing Authority’s (as defined under MISO’s
tariff) meter specifications;

accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices,reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the

Information.

contractors and agents in violation of this Section 4.

without a duty of confidentiality; (d) is independently developed or learned by the
Receiving Party without use of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information; (e) is
disclosed by the Receiving Party with the Disclosing Party’s prior written approval, or (f)
is required to be disclosed pursuant to a lawful order of a governmental authority, so longas the Party required to disclose the information provides the Party owning such
Confidential Information with timely prior notice of such requirement and provided that
such information will remain confidential for all other purposes under this Agreement.

SECTION 5. SERVICE CONDITIONS
5.1 Reactive Control
5.1.1 Transmission Owner and Interconnection Customer recognize and further
agree that Interconnection Customer and Transmission Owner have a mutual
responsibility for maintaining voltage at each Interconnection Point, in
accordance with Good Utility Practice, the requirements herein and any
applicable reliability standards.

TAXABLE PROJECT
THIS CONTRIBUTION IN AID OF CONSTRUCTION AGREEMENT (the "Agreement")
is made between Great River Energy, a Minnesota cooperative corporation ("GRE") whose address is
12300 Elm Creek Boulevard, Maple Grove, MN 55369-4718, and ITC Midwest LLC, a Michigan
limited liability company ("ITCMW") whose address is 123 5th Street SE, Cedar Rapids, Iowa 52401,
and is effective on the last date of execution indicated on the signature page(s), subject to the terms
hereof. GRE and ITCMW may be referred to individually herein as a "Party" and collectively as the
"Parties."
Recitals
A. ITCMW is the owner of certain poles and structures in Section 5, Township 102 North,
Range 32 West of the 5th P.M., Martin County, Minnesota, on which there is now attached GRE's 69
kV, three-phase circuit consisting of wires and appurtenances owned by GRE;
B. GRE has a project to rebuild and add OPGW to its FE-FD 69 kV transmission line into
the Fox Lake Substation;
. GRE has asked ITCMW to rebuild the tap from FE-FD structure number one going north into
the Fox Lake Substation to accommodate GRE's OPGW addition and line reconductoring;
A. ITCMW will rebuild the existing structures north of GRE's FE-FD structure number one
to the Fox Lake Substation as described on the attached Exhibit A (the "Work"); and
B. ITCMW is willing to perform the Work, provided it is paid for the cost of doing so.
Agreement
In consideration of the grants, covenants and agreements herein, the Parties agree as follows:
1. Work under this Agreement cannot commence until the filing with and acceptance of
this Agreement by, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC").
2. Upon receipt of payment of the Projected Cost (as defined below), GRE authorizes ITCMW
to proceed with the Work.
3. GRE shall pay ITCMW for the total cost of the Work, which shall include the cost of all labor,
overhead, rental costs, fees, design, permitting, administrative and engineering costs, taxes and the cost
of materials and equipment used to complete the Work. ITCMW estimates the cost of the Work to be
One Million One Hundred Six Thousand Five Hundred Forty-Nine Thousand and 50/100
1Dollars ($1,106,549.50) (the "Projected Cost"). GRE's payment of the Projected Cost is due to ITCMW
upon acceptance of this Agreement by FERC. ITCMW shall invoice GRE upon FERC acceptance of
this Agreement and GRE shall pay the invoice within ten (10) days indicating that the payment is for
ITCMW Project Name Fox Lake Tap Rebuild.
4. If the actual cost of the Work is less than the Projected Cost paid by GRE, ITCMW will, within
one hundred and eighty (180) days after completion of the Work, refund the excess to GRE. If the actual
cost of the Work exceeds the Projected Cost paid by GRE, GRE shall pay ITCMW the balance of the
actual cost of the Work within thirty (30) days of receipt of an invoice from ITCMW.
5. GRE's payment for the Work will be classified as a Contribution In Aid of Construction
("CIAC") payment, which is intended to cover the full cost of the Work. The estimate includes a gross-
up based on the current annual tax rate. The tax gross-up was calculated in the following method:
Current Tax Rate x (Gross Income Amount - Present Value Depreciation Amount) / (1 —Current Tax
Rate). While the estimate is intended to cover the entire tax obligation, GRE agrees to reimburse
ITCMW for such additional taxes, including penalty and interest payments, if any, imposed by the
Internal Revenue Service or other taxing authority with jurisdiction over the Work within thirty (30)
days of notice provided by ITCMW of such tax obligation.
6. ITCMW shall plan, schedule, and perform the Work and ITCMW shall solely determine the
manner and method of the Work. ITCMW shall use commercially reasonable efforts to promptly commence
and diligently pursue completion of the Work. ITCMW shall keep GRE advised periodically as to the
progress of the Work and any material increase in the Projected Cost. GRE may, at any time, request a
progress report from ITCMW. If any event occurs that will materially affect the time for completion of the
Work, or the ability to complete the Work, ITCMW shall promptly notify GRE of such event. In such
circumstances, ITCMW, within thirty (30) calendar days of such notice, shall convene a technical meeting
with GRE to evaluate alternatives to ensure timely completion. Notwithstanding the foregoing, GRE
acknowledges and understands that many factors outside the control of either Party may impact scheduling.
ITCMW will take commercially reasonable efforts to meet any projected deadlines, but expressly disclaims
any specific results. Nothing in this Agreement shall limit ITCMW from utilizing the services of
subcontractors, as it deems appropriate, to perform its obligations under this Agreement; provided, however,
ITCMW shall remain primarily liable for the performance of such subcontractor. All Work performed by
ITCMW or its subcontractor(s) will be performed in accordance with Good Utility Practice. "Good Utility
Practice" means any of the practices, methods, and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of
the electric industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods, and acts which, in the
exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known to the time the decision was made, could have
been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices,
reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice,
method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally
accepted in the region.
7. Either Party may request information, documents, or data regarding the Work for internal
business use or otherwise as required to meet regulatory obligations, which request(s) shall not be
unreasonably withheld.
8. ITCMW shall not be responsible for delays caused by strikes, work stoppage, lockouts, acts of
God (including inclement weather), delays attributable to GRE or GRE's employees, agents, contractors
or affiliates, other public or private utilities, the permitting or escorting authorities, or by any other
cause beyond the control of ITCMW; nor will ITCMW be responsible for delays that
2ITCMW, in its sole discretion, determines to be necessary for reasons of safety and/or system
requirements.
9. This Agreement is contingent upon ITCMW obtaining all necessary permits and authority to
perform the Work. In the event ITCMW fails to satisfy this condition precedent, no Work shall
begin and ITCMW shall refund the initial payment of the Projected Cost to GRE without further
obligation or recourse by either Party.
10. GRE accepts full responsibility for all environmental costs and disposition/disposal relating to
the Work and its associated equipment, except to the extent that the incurrence of such costs is the result
of ITCMW's negligence or willful misconduct. ITCMW makes no representations or warranties as to the
environmental hazards or condition of the land where the Work is to be performed.
11. Except for the payment obligations set forth in this Agreement, to wit, Section 4, which
shall survive this Agreement, The Parties' obligations under this Agreement shall terminate on the
date of completion of the Work.
12. EXCEPT AS OTHERWISE PROVIDED IN THIS AGREEMENT, ITCMW DISCLAIMS
ANY AND ALL WARRANTIES OR REPRESENTATIONS PERTAINING TO THE WORK THAT
ARE NOT EXPRESSLY SET FORTH IN THIS AGREEMENT, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED
TO EXPRESS OR IMPLIED WARRANTIES AS TO FITNESS OR DESIGN AND ALL
EQUIPMENT PROVIDED HEREUNDER WILL BE PROVIDED AS-IS.

law fully indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Party and its respective corporate parents and
affiliates, employees, agents, contractors, officers, directors, and/or members and managers, as the case
may be, (for purposes of this section, "Indemnitee(s)") from and against all claims, losses, demands,
causes of action, enforcement proceedings, suits, and other liabilities of any nature, including but not
limited to personal property damages, personal injuries or deaths, and including related expenses, costs
and reasonable attorneys' fees to the extent arising out of, resulting from, or caused by: (a) negligent acts,
errors or omissions, or willful misconduct of the Indemnitor, its employees, agents, contractors or
affiliates; or (b) a breach by Indemnitor or any of its employees, agents, contractors or affiliates of any

15. At all times during the performance of the Work, each Party shall be responsible to secure

liability insurance in an amount of at least one million dollars ($1,000,000) prior to the
3commencement of the Work. GRE shall secure and maintain a policy of general commercial

17. Each notice, demand, request, consent, approval, disapproval or other communication
